TikTok hides objectionable videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18
Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok is censoring videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet&#39;s independence or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian says.
In the documents that turned out to be the publication, it is said that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance) is using the application to promote the goals of China&#39;s foreign policy abroad.
The bulk of violations related to China&#39;s policy fall under &quot;incitement to hatred.&quot;
In each case, TikTok places objectionable posts in a context that fits the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look like censorship.
For example, the prohibition against criticizing China&#39;s socialist system falls under the general prohibition of &quot;criticizing or attacking the policies and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.&quot;
The ban on mentioning the Tiananmen Square incidents or the Cambodian genocide falls under &quot;distorting the history of China or other countries.&quot;
The document also lists the banned names of twenty &quot;foreign leaders or statesmen&quot;, including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, American Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hee, Indonesian President Joko Widodo and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi, the document says.
Prohibited material falls into two categories, the document says.
Posts from the first category are deleted by social network administrators and may result in user blocking.
Not too severe violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
Representatives of ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer apply: &quot;We are currently using a localized approach for moderation, and we also involve independent local experts.&quot;
Russian TikTok users do not have specific restrictions on publications, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the Producer Center.
The Producer Center is one Russian media company that officially works with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers &quot;Producer Center&quot; are coordinated with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without approval, reports Bogdanov.
When asked whether it is possible to speak out about politics or Putin on TikTok, Bogdanov answers in the affirmative and says that he has seen such publications.
Roman Zaripov, founder of Our Didgital agency, agrees with Bogdanov: &quot;The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: you cannot post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on.&quot;
But under these rules, you can bring any content that the moderators do not like, Zaripov notes.
Zaripov&#39;s agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
According to the user agreement, only people over the age of 13 can use TikTok.
Social network administrators check their age using artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account can be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of the WeWork coworking space.
