Another 218 numbers were blocked, and in 59 cases they imposed restrictions on the use of financial services.
The deputy head of the information security department of the Central Bank, Artem Sychev, said that a wide range of Russian banks had encountered the number substitution.
He explained that operators do not always respond to the Central Bank&#39;s warnings about fraudulent calls, citing the absence of such an obligation in the Law on Communications.
Otkritie Bank, Rosbank and Alfa-Bank confirmed information about an increase in the number of fraudulent calls with number spoofing.
According to the press service of Beeline, some of the information about fraudulent calls transmitted by the Central Bank was incorrect: the lists included numbers that are actually used by banks to communicate with clients.
Blocking them would lead to disruptions in the work of the organization.
Artem Sychev said that the Central Bank plans to create a database of fraudsters&#39; numbers, which the telecom operator will contact with each call to check the number.
He explained that in order to create such a base, it would be necessary to amend the legislation.
