Pavel Ustinov joined the pickets in support of the persons involved in the &quot;Moscow case&quot;
Actor Pavel Ustinov has joined a series of one-man pickets &quot;Freedom for all&quot;, which are being held on Friday near the building of the Russian presidential administration on Staraya Square in Moscow, an Interfax correspondent reports.
A series of pickets began on September 18 in support of Ustinov himself and has continued every day since then.
At present, the protesters, replacing each other, stand holding a poster with the inscription &quot;Freedom to all&quot; and the names of those convicted and arrested after uncoordinated rallies in Moscow in the summer of 2019.
In addition to Ustinov, the poster includes the names of Yegor Zhukov, Kirill Zhukov, Danil Beglets, Evgeny Kovalenko, Konstantin Kotov, Ivan Podkopaev, Aidar Gubaidulin, Alexei Minyailo, Sergei Fomin, Samariddin Vladjabov, Nikita Chirtsov, Eduard Malyshevsky.
On September 16, the Tverskoy Court of Moscow sentenced 24-year-old Ustinov to 3.5 years in a general regime colony on charges of using violence against an OMON soldier of the Russian Guard at an uncoordinated rally on August 3 in central Moscow (part 2 of article 318 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
After that, on September 20, at the request of the Prosecutor General&#39;s Office, the court changed Ustinov&#39;s measure of restraint from detention to a recognizance not to leave the place.
Thus, the petition for the release of Ustinov received more than 112 thousand signatures per day.
Theater and film artists started a flash mob in support of a colleague.
On September 18, a queue lined up to take part in a solo picket in solidarity with the actor.
Human rights activists, journalists, scientists, teachers, doctors, Orthodox priests demanded that the case be reconsidered.
As Ustinov&#39;s sister Yulia told Interfax, her brother does not plan to speak at a rally on September 29 in the capital in support of the defendants in the &quot;Moscow case&quot;.
Sanctions shipments to Russia fell 100 times
The government of the Russian Federation calculated that the supply of agricultural products and food to Russia from countries that fell under the Russian food embargo decreased since 2013 by more than 100 times.
According to a report sent to Russian President Vladimir Putin, in the first half of 2019, 31 thousand tons of products were imported from the sanctioned countries against 3 million 442.2 thousand tons in the same period in 2013, Interfax reports.
At the same time, the cost of imported products decreased to $ 226.5 million from $ 4 billion 975.5 million, respectively.
We are talking about the supply of goods that did not fall under the embargo.
As indicated in the report, the dropped volumes of products prohibited for import were compensated by an increase in imports from the CIS countries, Africa, Southeast Asia, and Serbia.
Recall that at the end of August, the government extended until December 31, 2020, the validity of the rules for the destruction of agricultural products, raw materials and food, which are prohibited from being imported into Russia as part of counter-sanctions.
In a document posted on the official portal of legal information, it was noted that the rules were extended for one more year - from December 31, 2019 to December 31, 2020.
Initially, the order to destroy the sanction was applied to products from the USA, EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Later, from August 13, 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein &quot;joined&quot; this list, and from January 1, 2016 - Ukraine.
A decree signed by Putin on the destruction of the &quot;sanctions&quot; (products that fell under the food embargo that Moscow imposed in response to the West&#39;s anti-Russian sanctions), which was illegally imported into the country, came into force in 2015.
In turn, the government allowed to destroy the &quot;sanctioned&quot; food in any legal way.
As the sanctions of the West persisted, the Russian Federation also extended its retaliatory measures.
At the same time, this measure does not apply to products that citizens import for personal use.
The ban does not apply to the import of goods for personal consumption weighing up to 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Presidential Council for the Development of Civil Society and Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov previously called the destruction of food &quot;simply immoral&quot;, and this, in his words, has a negative impact on the upbringing of people.
Moreover, in early June, Rospotrebnadzor came up with an initiative to prohibit the destruction of foodstuffs fit for consumption.
After that, a similar recommendation to the government was made by the Human Rights Council under the President of the Russian Federation.
And the Deputy Prime Minister of the Russian Federation Alexei Gordeev said that it is wrong to destroy food products, and we need to think about how to use them for their intended purpose, having evaluated the quality.
Firm CEO found guilty of tax evasion
By the verdict of the Leninsky District Court of the city of Cheboksary, the director of LLC &quot;Land and Law&quot; Vyacheslav Morozov was found guilty of committing crimes under paragraph &quot;b&quot; of Part 2 of Art. 199 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (tax evasion from an organization by including deliberately false information in the tax return, committed on an especially large scale) and Part 2 of Art. 327 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (falsification of an official document granting rights and releasing from obligations, in order to use it, committed in order to conceal another crime and facilitate its commission).
This was reported by the press service of the Investigative Department of the TFR in Chuvashia.
From January 2008 to December 2009, Vyacheslav Morozov entered information on outstanding transactions in the tax accounting documents of the LLC.
According to the fictitious documents, the company incurred additional costs, and, therefore, the amount of value added taxes and corporate income taxes payable was reduced by 11.2 million rubles.
Vyacheslav Morozov was sentenced to 3.5 years&#39; suspended imprisonment.
